1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;The Barber Manufacturing Heritage&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Barber Manufacturin
2 CONC g Company, Incorporated, founded in 1894 by Frederick T. Barber, has flourished through four generations of family ownership and management. This company's longevity, in an industry dominated by giant manufacturers, can be attributed to continuall
2 CONC y practicing the principles of its founder&amp;hellip;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;produce the highest quality product available and build close relationships with the customer.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: '
2 CONC trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Over the years, the corporation's leadership has had the foresight and ability to adapt the company's products to the needs of the market. F
2 CONC or example, in 1906, Fred purchased a patent for a spring assembly for upholstered furniture-coil springs mounted on a steel bar. At the same time, Grand Rapids, Michigan, was a hub for furniture manufacturers. As a partial result of the patent, Ba
2 CONC rber Manufacturing became a major furniture spring supplier in the Midwest. The focus of the company expanded from manufacturing springs for bedding to manufacturing springs for the ever-growing furniture industry.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style
2 CONC ="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Always listening to the customer, Barber Manufacturing produced custom designed springs tailored to the customer's individua
2 CONC l requirements. In addition to producing springs for bedding and furniture, the company expanded into automobile seating and later, school bus seating.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; fo
2 CONC nt-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Fred's son and successor, Wilson Barber, better known as Wick, succeeded his father as president in 1940. Wick continued to improve both the company's product line and prosperity. He desi
2 CONC gned and patented the Per-Fect Spring Unit, a popular spring assembly used in office seating. The design was so popular, the company had to build an addition to its manufacturing plant to supply the demand.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-f
2 CONC amily: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;With an eye on the future of the market, Barber Manufacturing maintained its edge in the furniture spring industry throughout the 19
2 CONC 40s and 1950s under Wick's leadership.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Wick died in 1964, passing the leadership of the com
2 CONC pany to his son, John Wilson Barber, Jr. Under John's guidance, the company not only expanded its product line, but it enlarged its sales territory, too. In the early 1970s Barber Manufacturing bought a second facility and began manufacturing sinuo
2 CONC us wire, a "zig zag" spring used in furniture.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;Besides manufacturing sinuous wire, the comp
2 CONC any broadened its position in the furniture industry by adding Bonnell Coil Innersprings for sofa sleepers to its product line in the late 1970s and early 1980s. Barber Manufacturing also added a distribution facility in Conover, North Carolina an
2 CONC d further increased its sales territory from the Midwest to the South and the West Coast.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;I
2 CONC n the 1990s, the company's top management found a way to capitalize on its many years of experience with the Marshall Unit in the furniture industry by producing an improved version of it for the bedding industry. The company began to convert exist
2 CONC ing equipment and added new, state-of-the-art equipment to manufacture the Barber Individually Encased Coil Innerspring. This product, coupled with the revised version of the Bonnell Coil Innerspring and the Rigid Bar Coil Boxspring, brought the co
2 CONC mpany full circle as it expanded its customer base to again include the bedding industry.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebuchet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;I
2 CONC n 1993, John W. Barber, Jr., became the Chairman of the Board, and his four children assumed responsibility for the leadership of Barber Manufacturing. Son Jeff became President and CEO in 1993, son Jim served in sales and marking, and son Tom serv
2 CONC es as Cash Manager. Daughter Betsy served as Customer Service Manager until 2002 when she decided upon a career change. In 2006 Jeff's son, Jack, became the 5th generation to join the business.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p style="font-family: 'trebu
2 CONC chet ms', arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; line-height: 18px; letter-spacing: 0.8pt;"&gt;For more than 116 years, the company's product line has continually evolved to remain competitive in an increasingly complex market. In additio
2 CONC n to adapting to new markets, the company's success in its chosen industries is attributed to its steadfast adherence to Fred Barber's philosophy&amp;hellip;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;provide a superior product and unparalleled customer support.&lt;/s
2 CONC trong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>1824 Brown St &amp;bull; P.O. Box 2454 &amp;bull; Anderson, IN 46016Phone 765-643-6905 &amp;bull; Fax 765-642-7480</line></content></metadataxml>
